../../controller/decisions/decision-012.json:3:  "reason": "This is a bootstrap controller decision after planning run-005, not a post-step review. `decision-011` killed the prior branch and ordered replanning, and the new planning artifacts consistently select the current compactness-rigidity falsification chain as the next canonical path. That chain now has a disciplined first gate before any new host-space audit: freeze one solution framework, one theorem-level endpoint, one temporal architecture, one bridge to the inherited local-energy floor, and one progress currency on a single ledger. The branch is therefore active again, the mission is not complete, and the correct next move is to open `step-008` on that setup gate rather than replan again or terminate.",
../../planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:39:- "Name the exact bottleneck term or theorem gap" is the right demand, but the chain does not require any quantitative target. Changing a bottleneck how much? By derivative count, exponent, cancellation, coercivity, compactness, or propagation time? Without a gain metric, attachment can still be cosmetic.
../../planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:74:The chain claims to rank mechanisms spanning critical elements, tensor routes, Lagrangian routes, and possibly stochastic structures. Those routes have different currencies of progress: compactness, coercivity, localization stability, propagation, or dynamical rigidity. Without a common scoring rubric, "ranking" is largely evaluator preference disguised as output discipline.
../../planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:13:- `L^3` is not just one more critical space on a list. It already sits next to very strong endpoint regularity results, so any minimal-element program there has to explain why those results do not already collapse the route or why the hypothetical critical element evades them only in a very specific way.
../../planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-02.md:31:The kill condition is too aggressive in one direction and too permissive in another. It is too aggressive because a promising route might only reveal the right rigidity quantity after the minimal object is formulated. It is too permissive because merely "naming" a Tao-sensitive lever is not progress unless one can state its sign, monotonicity, coercivity, or contradiction mechanism on the intended class of solutions.
